            <span class="type">Biography</span>
        

        <div class="tile-content rich-text"><p>I undertookÂ my undergraduate studies at Corpus Christi College, Cambridge, gaining a BA in medical science in 2000 before studying clinical medicine at Addenbrooke's Hospital, Cambridge.Â I qualified as a doctor in 2002, and moved to Nottingham forÂ my Basic Surgical Training.Â I moved to Oxford in May 2006 to take up a position with the <a class="external-link" href="http://www.transplantevidence.com" target="_blank" title="CET site">Centre for Evidence in Transplantation (CET)</a> as a clinical research fellow in transplant surgery, during which timeÂ I completedÂ my Master of Surgery (MChir) thesis with the University of Cambridge. On returning to higher surgical training I have remained on the staff of the CET and am now the Deputy Director.</p>
<p><span>IÂ was recently awarded an NIHR Academic Clinical Lectureship to run alongside the remainder ofÂ my clinical training with the University of Oxford. </span></p>
<p><span>MyÂ researchÂ interests lie in evidence-based transplant surgery, andÂ I have completed several large systematic reviews relating to the optimisation of post-transplant immunosuppression.Â Â </span></p>
<p><span>Along with the continuation of my systematic review work, IÂ will be working on the design of the Consortium for Organ Preservation in Europe (COPE) trials of novel organ preservation techniques, as well as the development of new trials in organ transplantation.</span></p>
<p>I will also be working with the <a class="external-link" href="http://www.lindalliance.org/" target="_blank" title="James Lind Alliance">James Lind Alliance</a>Â on a Priorities Setting Partnership (PSP) to bring together patients and healthcare professionals in the prioritisation of research topics in kidney transplantation.</p>
<p>Â </p></div>

